Answer choice: \boxed{{letter}}
Based on the retrieved evidence, there is no mention of bexarotene being studied, approved, or showing efficacy in relapsing-remitting multiple sclerosis. All referenced treatments—such as cladribine, fingolimod, natalizumab, ocrelizumab, interferons, and corticosteroids—are supported by robust clinical trials and regulatory approvals specifically for RRMS. Bexarotene, primarily used off-label in cutaneous T-cell lymphoma, has no established role in MS treatment despite some theoretical interest in retinoid pathways affecting immune modulation. Therefore, the initial conclusion stands unchallenged by available data.
\boxed{\text{B}}

